[high] policies/secretsmanager_resource_policy_least_privilege.rego:68 (security)
AWS resource policies allow Principal.AWS to be a bare 12-digit account ID, and the collector preserves that as a principal string. principal_account_id only extracts account IDs from ARN-shaped principals, so a policy principal like "999999999999" is skipped by the cross-account checks instead of producing cross_account_principal_undocumented. The same helper shape is duplicated in the vendor, confidential, and privacy transfer policy-scope checks, so this is a direct bypass for a valid cross-account principal format.
Suggested fix: Extend principal_account_id to return the principal when principal_arn/principal string matches ^[0-9]{12}$, then add tests for bare same-account and cross-account principals in the generic, vendor, confidential, and privacy transfer policy packages.
Guidance: Fix the duplicated local principal_account_id helpers; do not introduce a shared Rego package because this repo deliberately keeps policy packages flat/selectively loadable. In policies/secretsmanager_resource_policy_least_privilege.rego, policies/secretsmanager_vendor_credential_policy_scope.rego, policies/secretsmanager_confidential_policy_scope.rego, and policies/secretsmanager_privacy_transfer_governance.rego, add an earlier principal_account_id(principal_entry) rule that reads arn := principal_arn(principal_entry) and returns arn itself when regex.match("^[0-9]{12}$", arn). Keep the existing ARN-split rule unchanged for ARN principals. Also patch policies/secretsmanager_privacy_subprocessor_posture.rego only if you need consistent helper behavior there, but note its documented-role check compares full principal ARN strings and bare account IDs should remain outside the documented role set unless explicitly supported by product requirements. Add regression tests in each affected *_test.rego: bare same-account "123456789012" should not trigger cross-account findings; bare cross-account "999999999999" should trigger the relevant finding; allow-list behavior must remain family-specific, with generic/vendor allow-lists respected and confidential having no cross-account exception.
