[medium] policies/secretsmanager_admin_principal_present.rego:82 (correctness)
Resource-policy checks ignore the statement effect even though the collector emits it. A Deny statement with secretsmanager:DeleteSecret currently satisfies admin_principal_present, so a policy with no administrative Allow can pass the admin-principal check; conversely, wildcard/cross-account Deny statements are reported as if they grant access in the scope policies.
Suggested fix: Add an allow_effect predicate such as lower(object.get(principal, "effect", "")) == "allow" and require it for admin_principal_present and for every violation that reasons about granted principal/action access. Add Deny-only regression tests.
Guidance: Treat only Allow statements as access grants. In every policy that reasons about resource-policy principal/action access, add a local helper such as allow_effect(principal_entry) if { lower(object.get(principal_entry, "effect", "")) == "allow" }. Require allow_effect(principal) inside admin_principal_present in policies/secretsmanager_admin_principal_present.rego and inside each violation body that flags granted access in policies/secretsmanager_resource_policy_least_privilege.rego, policies/secretsmanager_vendor_credential_policy_scope.rego, policies/secretsmanager_confidential_policy_scope.rego, policies/secretsmanager_privacy_transfer_governance.rego, and policies/secretsmanager_privacy_subprocessor_posture.rego. This includes wildcard principal, cross-account/cross-border principal, principal outside cleared/documented role set, and excess action checks. Do not default missing effect to Allow; the collector/test fixtures already emit "Allow", and a missing/unknown effect should not be treated as a grant. Add Deny-only regression tests proving a Deny DeleteSecret statement does not satisfy admin_principal_present and Deny wildcard/cross-account/excess-action statements do not emit scope violations, while existing Allow tests still fail/pass as before.
